  "prompt": "What does impairment of assets mean?",
  "response": "Impairment of assets refers to a significant and permanent decline in the value of an asset below its carrying amount (book value) on a company's balance sheet. This occurs when the asset's recoverable amount is less than its current book value. Key points include:\n\n1. Causes of impairment:\n- Damage to the asset\n- Technological obsolescence\n- Economic downturn\n- Reduced market value\n- Changes in business strategy\n- Adverse legal or regulatory environment\n\n2. Accounting treatment:\n- The asset's value is written down to its recoverable amount\n- A loss is recorded on the income statement\n- The asset's book value is reduced on the balance sheet\n\n3. Types of assets that can be impaired:\n- Property, plant, and equipment\n- Intangible assets\n- Goodwill\n- Investments\n- Receivables\n\n4. Impairment testing:\n- Companies must regularly assess assets for potential impairment\n- Follows accounting standards like GAAP or IFRS\n- Involves comparing the asset's carrying value to its recoverable amount\n\n5. Financial implications:\n- Reduces reported asset value\n- Decreases company's net worth\n- Can impact financial ratios and investor perception\n\nImpairment helps ensure financial statements accurately reflect an asset's true economic value.",
